gly identify with Democrats, as conservatives do with Republicans. This “sorting,” Levendusky contends, results directly from the increasingly polarized terms in which political leaders define their parties. Exploring its far-reaching implications for the American political landscape, he demonstrates that sorting makes voters more loyally partisan, allowing campaigns to focus more attention on mobilizing committed supporters. Ultimately, Levendusky concludes, this new link between party and ideology represents a sea change in American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical partiesxUnited States. 0aPolitical partieszUnited States. 0aVoting researchxUnited States. 0aVoting researchzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aliberal, liberalism, politics, political, philosophy, philosophical, academic, scholarly, research, democrat, democratic, conservative, republican, parties, party, poli sci, washington dc, ideology, ideological, voter, 1970s, contemporary, modern, 20th century, america, american, partisan, usa, united states, government, 2000s, sorting.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226473673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226473673/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles